@toyotausa 

i don’t fly home, 
even though i know how much easier it would be.

Fremont, Michigan probably doesn’t mean much to many, but it means a whole lot to me.
it took 3,350 miles in the truck over the weekend to take Petey to this place.

i spent 18 years trying to get as far away from it as possible, and now every time i leave, i drive about 15 under the speed limit holding back emotion.

i know these woods look fairly unremarkable, but this is my old cross-country course.
and i suppose it has a lot to do with the person i ended up becoming.
it is a place i learned a lot about winning, and a lot more about losing.
it is the first place i brought a baby Bailey.
and about 12 years later, him and Loki gave chase here.
so it means something to bring Petey here for the first time.

i never fly when i go home, because i like to see all the country in between this one and my other. 
i need to be reminded of the distance for some reason.
and i need Pete with me, for all the other reasons.

the midwest IS the best.
super proud to be from the mitten.

i have to believe in the power of good this app still has.

did you know the first time i saw petey, was inside this app.
i saw him covered in literal shit, with probably no chance at making it in this world.
and then i got him.

and the irony is not lost on me that where we live now, in our safe quaint farm home, is 35 minutes from where he was homeless.

99% of the time i hate this app and what it has become. but i know, in my tiny little corner of the internet away from all the dancing reels and pick me curation, my people still care.

@turquoisepawrescue has ran out of food. it’s where Pete came from and they don’t have food for the dogs or puppies.
and i know Petey’s next meal is in the cupboard. it doesn’t sit well with me that is not the reality for millions of animals.
i know there are so many causes and charities.
i can give you my word these are good humans fighting so hard.

if you can help, please join me, they just need amazon, chewy, or walmart orders.

thank you for being the good.
link is in my bio. 🐭

what do I do when I miss him? 

that's easy. i eat and i sleep and i go out and i stay up late and i watch the stars and i do my work and i procrastinate and i write and i make things and i speak and i stay quiet and i draw and i make mistakes and i do good things and i do awful things and i take naps and i stay in and i travel the world and i sit by his grave and i laugh and i smile and i cry and i hurt and i am completely one-hundred-percent me.
i have missed him so greatly and for so long that it is part of my identity.
there isn't a moment that i don't long for him. 

every day of my life is needing his presence, lightly covered with all of these bits and pieces.

i do everything when i miss him.

some people seem to be worried about Petey.
and my level of love and commitment to him.

i’m worried too.
because he has a memory foam bed and two fuzzy blankets on it.
and a food and treat closet.
and we spend every day all day snuggling, chasing each other, watching movies, snow shoeing, camping, eating mango, traveling the country, chasing the 4-wheeler at the farm, and being smothered with love.

my work is condensed. i don’t leave Petey every day to go to work for 8 hours.
instead, every couple months i leave for 8 days.
and i certainly don’t waste time on the internet bullying others, when i could be spending it with my dog 🙃

Pete is just fine back home cozy with our shared favorite human. don’t worry bout him k?
instead, head over to my next post to see some dogs who actually need you to worry about them. ♥️

egypt is really special.
it is everything i dreamt of since i was a child.
tombs, pyramids, museums, kings, queens, and a few camels.
i even saw a mummified dog, and he looked just like my Petey.

this is my favorite photo.
because i don’t really know how to take a photo or tell a story without a dog.
i call him black dog.
and he lives at the Sphinx, because he doesn’t have a home and this is all he knows.

and here he is, smiling.
i liked his spirit.

tonight with new family and friends, a little boy i had just met crawled on the floor towards a sleeping Petey.

unprompted he said to Pete,
‘you are a squeaky mouse.
a little mouse.
hi mousey.’

a few eyes darting around the room landed on me. no one said anything.
and my chest flooded.

christmas eve always hurts.
this year has almost gone,
and not all our friends and family made it.
never take for granted the people you love.
be there, go slow.
and love the giver more than the gift.

from me, Pete, and our angel who never leaves us,
happy christmas.

if there were words to say it,
i wouldn’t have to photograph it.

*i wrote this before i came to Portugal for the new year. it was supposed to be 48hrs, in and out. 20 inches of snow back home and delayed/cancelled flights…it turned into 7 days in this amazing country of rolling green hills and coastal lines.

i’m lucky to be here. i’m grateful for the privilege to travel.

back with my Pete

the dead of winter.
those words are so incredibly heavy.
the dead.

for me, it is the darkest coldest season of a life.
i dont know how to separate the bad memories that happened in these months from all the sunshine filled snow packed winter fun Instagram seems to have.

the cold reminds me of what it felt like when he left.
and the snow reminds me of how frozen the earth became around his grave.
i don’t like how this season blankets everything.
i just wait for it to be over…
but oh how he loved winter.

we are a couple days away from celebrating the life of Petey.
my best friend. my little bear.
a soft soul born in a hardest time.

his breed mix demands he loves the snow; i can’t get him out of it.
he buries his face in the powder,
he rolls around on the ice.
we wait for the blizzards to time our adventures.
we aren’t wasting these months locked inside sitting frozen in pain.

both my boys have seen things in this season i could not.
but i can change. i have changed.
i have Pete,
life, in the dead of winter.

to me, you are still nothing more than a little boy who is just like a hundred thousand other little boys.
and I have no need of you.
and you, on your part, have no need of me.
to you, I am nothing more than a fox like a hundred thousand other foxes.
but if you tame me, then we shall need each other. 
to me, you will be unique in all the world.
to you, I shall be unique in all the world.

if you tame me, it will be as if the sun came to shine on my life.
i shall know the sound of a step that will be different from all the others.
all other steps send me hurrying back underneath the ground.
yours will call me.

it is not some cute game of who saved who.
2 years ago a boy was born to take over watch.
just took me some time to realize.

happy birthday to the most kind, patient, trusting and gentle dog earthside.
you saved my life, Pete.

things i know about healing-
when you want to run, stay.
when you want to hide, open up.
when you think you're done, go a little further.

when you think you can open your heart again, do it anyway.

standing in line for tea with Meg just now, not knowing what to say about this photo.
only that i miss you to my bones.
and how you would have loved this amazing country under your well-worn paw pads.
the mountains you would have climbed.
the glacial lakes you would have swam.

with kind eyes she said how special the trip was.
and i said how wild to think about when we first met 8 days ago.

and then Meg said,
you can live a lot of life in a short time.

and i thought of you, and your time on this earth.
so i said,
yeah. if you are doing it right.

remember that a broken heart is still a heart that beats, a heart that still has value.

and sometimes, through the splinters, through the cracks, and all the tiny, shattered pieces, sometimes a broken heart bleeds in full color in a world of black and white.
and sometimes, as it overflows, it spills onto the earth and heals the ground beneath.

sometimes, actually, all the times…
a heart that has been broken can be a very powerful thing.

it all comes down to what you do with it.
i’m out here loving every dog i can, Mouseman.
this is what i’m doing with it.

i know a lot of pretty girls, beautiful women, and stunning souls.

it has nothing to do with their hair, the color of their eyes, the clothes they wear, or the shape of their bodies.

it’s the integrity of their hearts, the willingness to be vulnerable, and the amount of fight they have to show up.

i don’t have shit for you in the realm of makeup tips, workout ideas, or really much else.
but i can talk to you about the love of a dog.
and i can offer you a family to join.

i’ve travelled all over this earth, and i’m not done yet.
i’m telling you, i’ve seen beauty of all kinds,
and these humans are a sight to be seen.

yesterday i saw the face of a sweet friend for the first time since she said goodbye to her dog.
and although we didn’t talk about it, i saw it.

through a video call i could see the pain in her eyes.
and hear the softness in her voice on the verge of a break.
and i watched grief sitting next to her and all around her at once. wrapping its dark arms tightly.

and i thought to myself,
‘she’s never looked more beautiful to me, as she does in this moment.’

because this life is not about being happy.
but rather love.
and recently i learned love cannot exist without beauty.
the beauty of a beautiful human wearing the beautiful loss of her beautiful dog.
this only happens one way, and it’s a hard way.

there’s no filter or editing or any other way i want to see her.
i know losing B aged me.
you can see it on face and for those with eyes for it, on my heart.
it’s a record of our love, and i’m so grateful to look this way.

Jenna girl, you’ve never looked more beautiful than you do right now.
this only happens one way, and it’s the hard way.

a few days ago, we became a family of four.

please say hi to Bruce Crow,
the black german shepherd.

two years ago today, you made me a momma again.
this world does not deserve you, Pete.

you are, and will continue to be, the most gentle choice my heart has ever made.

happy got you day. 🤎

the grieving are time travelers.

for it takes only one song.
one smell.
one sound.
one moment.
and we are suddenly right back there with them.

you sent me a little time machine, didn’t you.
a little shadow mouse running around my feet as i do the dishes.
his groans when he moves in his sleep.
and those eyes that are far too aged for a puppy.
i don’t know what is him and what is you.
and it hurts so very good.

i’ve been spending these days bouncing back and forth between then and now.
for the grieving are time travelers.

a portrait of an older brother.
exhausted, but so in love.

it is hard to believe everything will work out ok if your only experience is things ending badly.
how can you draw on hope, if your back catalogue is only filled with loss.

the answer-
draw on someone else's hope.
see how their story ended well,
and believe yours can end the same.

per Egyptian law, tourism police may accompany you at any point.
they ride with you on the bus, they eat with you, they visit sites with you.

after a few stops, our police officer quietly told our guide, Hany, that we should keep moving to avoid crowds. and Hany having spent two tours with me, knew that wasn’t something he was going to say to me.
or my people.

because my people sat in the sand, or on the disgusting concrete, or diverted their paths just to sit with a few forgotten souls. they didn’t shy away when ticks were jumping in between ear rubs, or give up on the more fearful timid ones.
what is deemed street-smart went out the window when a bleeding horse belonging to an unknown man needed to be untied.
so they untied him.

they say you can judge a place by the manner in which they treat their animals. and i tried my hardest to see Egypt for what i dreamt it to be. and while i did see those wonderful things, i saw them saturated in animal abuse and an overwhelming complete disregard for animal welfare.

that same police officer said something to our guide in Arabic, and i asked what it was.
and he said, 
‘Mr. Hany i never really noticed the dogs. or maybe i didn’t think to like them. and these dogs don’t know these tourists, never have they seen them before, and yet their tails still wag. and these tourists take the time to feed them, to water them.
and the people here are watching them.
they have done more in these actions than one hour of yelling could do.
i see the dogs now, and i like the dogs Mr. Hany.’

starving dogs, hurt cats, abused camels, and a carriage horse emaciated so severely i am sure we witnessed one of his last days.

i share these atrocities, not for shock value.
but because one day you’ll find yourselves in a position not so different from where i stood.
i visited this same dog in this photo 2 months apart.
i told him how sorry i was.
i kissed him.
i said to be a good boy.
i said a silent plea that the next day someone else would come along and do the same. and that he would make it.

we have to try. we have to hope that maybe someone else sees us try. and then they try.
and then maybe one day-
may these animals forgive us.

with brothers no boundaries exist,
this thing i know.
and so here look closely my friends,

the sweet red fox held the little black crow.

Bruce is holding a squeaky mouse here.
@chewy sent it to Bailey, just a few months before he passed away.
and i’ve been holding it dearly ever since.
some of you might remember Loki never picking up a toy.
not until Bailey left us.
and one night he took this little blue mouse out to where his brother was buried.
Petey sometimes chooses it, out of all the toys, to bring to me.

Bruce gets his name from Bailey.
and Bailey got it from Bruce Willis.
a hero of mine. a fighter. a man of strength. and an energy B just had.
he was a little bit older than everyone. always had a minor cut on his face from going a little too hard. and would get into these modes- we called them Die Hard modes.

and then we started dressing him up as Batman every October.
once again, Bruce came back into play.
and when he left me, i wore the mask and Pete became Robin.

fast forward a year-
i love someone who knows none of this.
he never got to know this dog who changed me. who made me anything good i am.
and we decide to get Pete a baby brother.
feeling every possible feeling staring at another german shepherd, i asked,
‘what should we name him?’
and he said, ‘something strong, he’s going to be strong.
…how about Bruce?’

i am smiling even now.
i do not believe in coincidences.
the dark mouse rises.

i drove 103 miles just so my puppy could eat a new stick in a new place.

i guess you could say that’s been my life for the last 15 years.
driving from here to there, and then from there to here.

all these years in Toyotas, and i’m thinking of the places we went.
maybe my memory doesn’t serve me well with all the cool places i have seen,
or the people i have met-
but i can tell you every floppy or standup-eared good boy’s name who has been my precious cargo.

this has been my life.
and who knows how many thousands of miles i’ve driven,
just so my dog could eat a new stick in a new place.

i took this photo in a place i’ve been to one hundred times. there is Bailey fur in this sand.

as i laid down to take it, not knowing if i’d ever share it on social media with a bunch of strangers in exchange for little hearts, i thought to myself how much has changed.
even though i’m in the same place.
i’ve posted photos of this place for you, for years.
and i’m sorry to admit i was selling you a form of a lie.
take that word peace and extract from the definition,
as it was the opposite- disturbance.
disturbing.

my peak relevance on instagram coincides with my most toxic self.
i manipulated moments and photos to make a very painful life, look very beautiful.
and it worked.

2 years and 8 thousand followers less,
i’ve learned that this life only feels uneventful because it is no longer traumatic.
peace after hell can feel like that.

i keep my IG as a photographic journal of my dogs.
and some special people i’ve met.
i like the way my photos stitch together, i like going back and reading about Bailey.
i like remembering some good we all did together here.

and this won’t mean much to many, so i guess i’m talking to the few-
my heart does not forget when i was drowning, the ones who reached out a hand.
and i can’t blame the rest who looked the other way.
the ones who bought the lie.
because i was a great liar.

but i am also a good dog mom.
i am a good sister and daughter and granddaughter.
and i am lucky enough to be called a friend to a few humans around the world.
and this dog right here is a beating heart reminder of it all.
Pete, like Bailey, he has had to do more than one dog should.

Pete coming to me when everything was falling apart wasn’t some test,
it was simply an opportunity to practice all that i say i am.

if you knew time as well as i do,
you wouldn’t talk about wasting it.

never had a black dog before.
they’ve all been white; two so far.

Bruce is dark like the night sky without stars.
i take photo after photo and his face rarely shows, his features are sucked into the void.

everyone asked too soon, would i get another german shepherd.
no.
i couldn’t stand to see others,
their stance or gait were too familiar.
the shape of their head or movement of their tail.
it was too much.

a wound aged and festered for healing, i began the search.
Bruce’s mom, a sable. his dad, all black-
i knew no white could possibly show up, there would be nothing to remind me.
i am either dumb, or naive.

i’ve been out here living with Pete, my gentle perfect angel and Bruce, my little dark knight bull-in-a-china-shopping his way through his young life.

early Friday evening, my love and our dogs on the couch, settling in for a movie night. and he said,
‘did you see white fur is growing in between Bruce’s front paw?
where is that coming from?’

i didn’t want to talk about it.
i’ve noticed it for weeks now.
before i completely lost it, i just grabbed his paw and gently squeezed it saying hello to someone who maybe is saying hi back.
a light in the dark. a light that knows not how to go out.

i said, ‘i don’t know.
i guess i still don’t have a black dog. 
they’ve all been white, 3 so far.’

i will always celebrate this day.
i’m celebrating right now by streaming silent tears in the dark wanting to hold him,
but afraid to wake him.
it was the worst mistake i ever did make; to give him up.

but this day, this day marks when i came back for Pete.
and it is the day he forgave me.
and it is the day i made a promise-
i will never hurt you again.

he is my reminder, maybe he can help someone else tonight too,
you can say sorry.
and you can ask to make it right.

Hello. My name is Bruce.

*hi Bruce*

It has been three weeks since my last fish, on my honor, or may I be chopped up and made into soup.

this part, i will walk with you-
the trekking dogs of the Himals. 

i had 41 miles to think.
some of those miles i suffered so deeply i felt every inch of pain, deciding i wasn’t going to be able to finish this. 
some of those miles i felt light and free, smiling and laughing with friends.
and some of those miles i walked in silence, alone.

in these miles, were the dogs of Nepal.
showing up and fading away. some quick hellos and a few ear scratches, and some that settled in for the long haul. 
this is where i met Black Dog.

i found him sleeping in the sun by our porters.
i laid with him for a bit on the cold rock.
and then i kissed him what i thought was goodbye.

but then there he was at summit.
sharing meals and tail wags, i watched him decide which dogs were allowed near us, and i watched him take it too far.
i had empathy for those actions.
for protecting a family and maybe not always getting it right.

the dogs of Nepal, showing up and fading away-
this part, i will walk with you. 
i looked at Black Dog, i looked at myself.
and i looked at my group.
walking those miles without their dads.
without their moms.
without their best man.
without a sister.
without their dog.

because death has left so many of us out here walking feeling every inch of pain, thinking we cannot finish this.
healing has us sometimes feeling light and free, laughing with our friends.
and grief, that monster. it will have us walk so very many of these miles alone, in silence.

Black Dog took us all the way up. and all the way down.
and when we had to say goodbye, he chased the trucks. i silently wept as my heart stretched so far between us, it broke. 
i know it well, we don’t get to choose this part.

the free will of a mountain dog walking with strangers, protecting and offering silent companionship is a gift.
i hope maybe just a little bit, i am like Black Dog.
i hope he has started the journey back up, with a new soul to guide.

my Nepal family,
i am so proud of you.
you got so close to the sky we almost touched them.
your dog. your dad, sister, mom, and best man.
but since we are still earthside,
i’m here, Black Dog is here, if you’ll have us.

this part, we will walk with you.

pete’s face says it all.
bruce is six months old.

say a small prayer for us all.

you look happy.
the number one comment to my random pop ins here while i choose to fade away with my relevance in tow.

i know what time you are using for comparison.
when my smile didn’t quite reach my eyes.
and my laugh didn’t really sound like i found anything all that funny.

i look happy.
i’m photographing one of the great loves of my life, surrounded by the rest of the great loves of my life.
am i happy?
yeah. for sure. and i’m sad.
i’m healed and i’m in grief.
i got found and i still feel pretty lost.
and i can be light, and still be the darkest thing you’ve ever seen.

thank you. for caring about me.
i’m doing so well.
but if you aren’t feeling happy today,
could you follow me, off this app.
follow your petey into the tall grass.
none of this is about being just happy.
just happy…

no, i think we are meant for far more than that.
♡

i miss you so much, i forget that other people do too.

i called your grandma the other day and before we got off the phone she said,
hey i bought this giant picture frame and want all my grand pups in it,
can you send me photos of Bruce and Pete?

and i said, yeah, i should have a few of those laying around.

my competitive nature kicked in as i thought of my brother’s dogs, and the no doubt ranking system that must be in place in grandma’s heart.

so like any little sister would do, i playfully asked her,
ok but who is your favorite…

and Mousey,
there was a long pause on the other end of the phone.
and a small crack in the strongest woman’s voice as she said,
he’s not here anymore.

so while i miss you in every way a soul can be missed, i don’t carry it so much on my own anymore.

we miss you.
and grandma didn’t need to ask me for photos of you.
you were the first thing she put in there.

‘what do you do?’, she said.

and i laughed & clapped my hands.
i said, ‘1. i walk barefoot as much as possible
2. i paint in the afternoons, things that make me smile and
3. i wonder what my dogs think about when we go out wandering together.

‘i meant for a living.’ she said.

and i said, ‘i did too.’

will you take a moment?
promise me this.
that you'll stand by me forever.
but if, God forbid, fate should step in
and force us into a goodbye,
if you have children someday,
when they point to the pictures
please tell them my name.
tell them how the crowds went wild
tell them how i hope they shine.

long live Bailey. and all the mountains we moved.
i had the time of my life fighting dragons with you.

i will never get another dog.
that’s what i said.
when i lose Bailey, i’ll never get another dog.

i don’t want to love another.
or hold another.
kiss another.
photograph another.
i don’t want memories with another.

and that is wrong.
it is actually so fucking wrong.
if you knew Bailey, either you met him, or knew him here-
we know that dog would never
never 
want me to be alone.

it’s been almost one thousand days since that hurting girl said those words. and how many memories have you seen me make with these sweet boys?
how many of you sent hearts when i said Pete was home for good.
and when baby Bruce made his debut.
how hard have you rooted for me to make it.
for us to make it.

some of you are near where i was that dark november.
i know because that’s what fills my DMs.
you remember me when you are most scared and hurt.
when you are losing your soul, and you don’t want another.

but i don’t ever want to hear you talk like that.
you look at Pete, and then you look at Bruce,
and you remember there was one before.
and he always intended this for me,
to love another.

‘that’s your big brother, Petey.’

that’s what i used to tell him.
eventually when i moved the couch under these photos, he could reach them.
i’d come home to them hanging slightly crooked, and i’d grab glass cleaner to clean off nose smudges.

i don’t know what they would talk about.
but i bet it had something to do with me.

you take care of her.
ok. i’ve never looked after anyone. but i’ll try.
is she ok.
i don’t know. some days.
we miss you.
i’m right here.
make her smile. make her laugh.
i’m trying.

i came out of my bathroom one day to find him sitting here. and it’s still a very hard photo for me to take in.
i interrupted a private conversation between brothers.

and if you don’t get it. you won’t.
you won’t get it until you are sitting on a hill at 1am begging the universe for a shooting star to prove they aren’t gone.

and in this family, we collect shooting stars.
these little moments are not made up in my mind.
late at night looking up at the sky,

i say, ‘that’s your big brother, Petey.’

i have this skillset with seeing pain.
i’ve honed it in, sharpened it so well i can predict every emotion.
and i already know what will happen.

there is this hike in alaska, some of you have done it with me.
it is not what i would call easy.
but at the top, there is some mousey fur. i left it there.
and every single person who has walked past the entrance sign with me, has fought their way to the top. 

the part in the beginning feels okay, because we are all together. i hear talking and laughter.
the part in the middle feels a little harder, we are spread out.
and by the final push straight up, maybe it’s just you. it feels uncomfortable and you think maybe you are in the wrong place doing the wrong thing. 
and you can’t see the end, and you can’t see the top, 
but you remembered i gave you my word, that i am up there somewhere. waiting.

because i’ve done it before.
i’ve been here before.
but it is so hard to see so many of my friends in pain.
because it doesn’t have a damn thing to do with the hike- that pain in your legs, the strain in your back, the difficulty in your chest.
i see that weight you are carrying. and it’s not in your pack. 

if you let me hear your story and share your pain, i can help.
i think it is what i am meant to do.
i can hold space for the death of a loved one.
i can be your friend if you feel like you have none.
if you tell me what your butterfly tattoo means, i can remember why.

because for years you let me share my pain right here.
and you didn’t make me feel stupid.
and you let me remember him how i want, and you carry those pins on your packs up mountains he never got to explore.
so you see, when i was in that straight up part of the final push and i almost quit,
i heard you. and you were screaming his name so loud, it echoed.

i am stronger now,
and i can carry your weight.
i will make it to the top, look back, and see your struggle.
and i will yell at the top of my lungs as i see its wings flutter in the alaskan sun-

BUTTERFLY. Grace, there are butterflies up here.

i know haven’t talked about the day we got bruce. but i’d like to.

in february we flew to my hometown in michigan, where my mom picked us up.
we drove in a rainstorm down a muddy road towards a meeting place, and my heart was really anxious.
as if i haven’t been caring for dogs for 15 years on my own, i had some deep seeded doubt i could do it for this puppy.

i waited in a gas station parking lot shifting my weight from foot to foot in the pouring rain with no hood on.
and bailey’s old t-rex stuffy in my hand.
what if he doesn’t like me. what if i am bad. what if he runs away or gets hurt.
what if he overheats in his kennel.
what if he gets cancer and dies,
and i have to do this all over again.

interrupting those thoughts, this little black puff was handed to me.
i pulled him in tight against my coat and looked down at his gray eyes.
he kissed my nose and tucked his little head under my chin.
just then i looked over at my mom’s eyes swelling with tears, i’m guessing from watching of part of her daughter’s light come back.

and then we got in the car and drove away.
i said,
hi little baby. i am your mama. this is your dad.
that is grandma. and i am going to take you home to your brother now. 
and we will figure out the rest ok?

Bruce is 8 months old today.
and i still carry a lot of that pain and worry.
i wake up every morning thinking he could have died in the night.
i know it comes from years of trauma with Bailey.
i also know it’s normal, and i am working through it.

i realized the other day i only talk about Bruce in playful manners.
i joke about his bear-like size,
his dopey demeanor, 
or the constant terror he subjects his big brother to.
and like most jokes, it’s a cover for how deep the other emotions are.
because he is part of the most healing 8 months of my life.

i love him more than i ever thought i could, and i can admit now,
that he is his own dog all while reminding me so much of Bailey.
and though some bad things undoubtedly will come our way, this sweet boy doesn’t spend one second worrying about that.

the lesson my special boy carries-
it changes how you live, when you decide to love each other without knowing how it ends.

and because this place has a lot of heavy things being shoved down our feeds,
here is need a reminder, some paws and a dirt path can heal a lot.

tucked in my center console converted to a little bed for the littlest babies.

baby pete and baby squeaker.

but i couldn’t let them go.

you know, i took this photo three months after mousey died.
and yet, there he is.

somebody loses their somebody, every day.

i made a friend in New Zealand. one of my travelers.
after about a week together, at our farewell dinner, she said, how did you do it.
how did you make it.

and i stared at her knowing her dog, Brady, was alive at home waiting for her. and then i had a flashback to that night,
and i guess i could have lied to her.

but i leaned in and started to cry and said,
i screamed for him on the kitchen floor.
i didn’t eat.
i couldn’t sleep.
and i wanted to die. and i felt more alone than i thought was possible.

and she said,
i don’t think i can do it. i won’t make it.
and i said,
you will. and we will get you through it.

and then Brady got really sick. really fast.
i watched from across the country wondering what to do or what to say.
i thought of all the things people said to me. and how it was never enough. and it never helped. and so i couldn’t do that to her. i just said, ‘i know.’

somebody loses their somebody every day.
and i know a lot of dogs who have had to leave my friends behind broken-hearted. 
but there was something about this somebody, and her somebody that felt too painful for me.
i see a little too much of me in her.

on Brady’s last day,
i told her i would call on his precious name.
Mousey. we need you in New York right now.
i need you to be there.
and wait for him.
be the first face he sees, make sure he knows he’s not alone, he’s new to missing his momma. it’s going to be hard for a while.

and then i sat in tears waiting.
i bought wifi on the plane to make sure i was available.
my friend was outside with her boy, waiting for the medicine to take him to rest,
‘ally…

i just saw a mouse.
he ran across the driveway’

a sliver of comfort rushed over my nerves.
he’s such a good boy.
of course he’s there.
he went first, so he could be there.
and then Brady followed that little mouse up into the clouds.

i didn’t have anyone to ask to be there for my boy.
and it tore me apart thinking he was alone.
i just wanted to say, if you need, just call his name.

he can be there.
my somebody can wait for your somebody.

i heard this thing once.
and it scares the hell out of me.

that when we remember something, we are actually only remembering the last time we remembered it.

not the actual moment.

and over time, it can become skewed or different.
an unintentional exaggeration here or there. or a devastating detail forgotten and subsequently left out.

i’ve used this theory to my advantage. i think we all do.
i have taken something that is mostly built up of the hard times, and only held on to soft moments i found buried in there.
i have left behind broken people, only taking the whole parts i knew.
and i have listened to lies, while knowing some truth.
we take the good, and leave the bad.

November is the hardest time in my life.
the date rolls over on the night of October’s thirty first and i swear on my boys,
i can feel it in my chest while i lay in bed.
i’ve never needed a calendar to remember what the air feels like in this month.
i’ll never need a reminder that not only is a season about to change. that i am about to never be the same.

no matter how happy i am now, no matter how healthy my two dogs are now, and no matter how far i have taken myself away from a place i was once, it is November.
and i’m right back in that house.

i knew there was a chance i would forget something, that my heart was breaking and that history had proven that my brain would try to protect me.
block out some of the dark.
so i recorded a lot of our life back then.
i remember on this day i called for help to a stranger across the country.

i’ve told this story.
i haven’t exaggerated the moment.
no devastating detail forgotten and subsequently left out.

i want to remember this memory forever as it truly was.
and i want to share it with you now.
so that this wonderful light of my life never goes out.

🐭

know that i speak your name aloud everyday.
a combined hello and goodbye.

and perhaps a plea for your impossible return.

you are my boy. and your name is Bailey.

he told me to tell you something.

and i’m so small and little and new,
but i’m trying my best to remember.

he told me to tell you something.
something about biggie brothers and bigger cuddles.
that i’ll grow into my paws, not to worry.
to remember to do some of the same things, make sure mom sees you do it.

i think he said everything means something.
but i don’t really know anything.
he did say you aren’t alone and it’s not in your head.

it was all stars and a big dark sky when i came to this place.
i was pretty scared but he told
me i was going to be okay.
or maybe he told me to tell you,
that you are going to be okay.
i’m trying my best to remember.

then he put this little special light inside my chest.
can you see it shine out through my eyes.
he gave it to me to keep.
he let me rest my little head into his big white body,
and then he nudged me on my way.

and he told me to tell you something.
or maybe he just sent me.
i’m trying my best to remember.

this was it. this was our last day together.

a few sacred goodbyes were allowed.
your aunt Jacque was across town teaching a class with your photos all around her and people wore your pins.
members of the Navajo Nation held a smudging ceremony preparing for your transition.
and candles were lit all around the world by these friends we collected on the internet.
all for you, Mousey.
and i was never more proud to be your mama.

if you can imagine our favorite song about to end,
or that last grain of sand about to slip through the hourglass-
all these people, Bailey- well they gave us a few more chords to listen to.
a few more seconds of falling sand in slow motion.
and i don’t ever forget that. and the words thank you fall so short.

covered in blankets on frosty grass, we made shapes out of clouds and named the crows in the trees.
surrounded by white flowers and a wood fire, we made promises i’m still right here keeping.

i would live this day every day for all my days.
if you let me.
but that horrible monster Time won’t allow for it.
he just keeps going.
and i’ve had to live so many days since, without you.
one thing Time will not take from me; our memories,
your memory.

when tonight rolls over with the new moon,
the time will read 1:11, it’ll be November 14th and
i will be right here howling for you.
tomorrow i will hurt. but today is not tomorrow.

today i will remember the honor it was to sit with the boy i tell myself was the most loved boy who ever was.

i love you Bailey.

Bailey, nothing is louder than my heart for you.
three years.

as you swipe through these photos you’ll see a puppy become what looks like a dog, but is still wholly a puppy.

you’ll see a rez dog become a big brother, even though now he’s smaller.

you’ll see moments i never really got around to sharing on here because i had started to live my life off here.

someone asked me the other day, is Bruce ok? you never post him.

is Bruce ok.
yeah, friends. he was just busy swimming in his pool, chasing lizards, biting his brother, watching the crows that live in our arroyo, traveling across states, eating 3 bones a day, learning to walk on a leash, exploring the mountains, stealing yogurt from the counter, playing fetch with squeaky balls, getting on the bed when he knows he shouldn’t, and making his family so incredibly happy.

one year ago he was born while i slept on a sail boat in Egypt.
she confirmed, ‘one large all black male’. 
smiling under my blanket, i said okay. i’ll be there soon. i’ll be his mama.

and nothing has been the same since.
you cannot imagine the happiness that lives inside his heart. and what he brings to our lives every day. i’ve tried to quantify it-
44 weeks of Pete running to Bruce’s kennel every morning, let him out let him out! 
16 minutes of brother time before he gives me the look to put him back, already annoyed.
559 bones.
26 new toys.
and 100 times a day i yell, BOYS!!! and they both look at me guilty as hell.

oh, and add in 4 very very happy hearts.

one boy does all this. and he is my boy.
happy birthday Bruce, my dark knight. 🦇

i dreamt of you.
my sweet little crow.
my little batman.
some of us know exactly where you got that little cape tied around your neck 🖤 

one year old today, thank you for being the hero we deserve.

winter solstice ✧  bruce and pete’s little rabbit hops in fluffy snow.
i think that says everything. what a quiet happy life it is.

a walk without a dog.

we took our friend along with us on this one. me, my two boys,
and her, without her boy.

and every step we took i thought it, but didn’t say it.
i knew it, because i know it.
and i felt it, because i still feel it.

i remember the first burn of not having Bailey and watching my friend’s dogs run around me.
it hurt. it made me happy, made me sad.
it helped. it made it worse.
and when it boiled down to it, it just felt unfair.

all this walking i’ve been doing, i’ve learned to carry both.
she misses her dog, the same as me. i’m just a little further down this path already. and somewhere along my way, when i felt my most alone, i picked up these two stinkers. 

she’s a few months out and me, a few years, but some times these walks feel just as hard. 
so we keep walking.
